04599nam a22006135i 9780814788882DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19941994nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147888827 a10.18574/97808147888822doi  a(DE-B1597)548429  a(OCoLC)44962791  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aF264.W8 S48 1994 7aHIS0361202bisacsh04a975.6/671 aShirley, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Congregation Town to Industrial City :bCulture and Social Change in a Southern Community /cMichael Shirley. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe American Social Experience ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tONE. The Congregational Community of the Moravians -- tTWO. The Congregation and a Changing Economy -- tTHREE. Manufacturing and Community in Salem -- tFOUR. Community Culture in Antebellum Salem -- tFIVE. The Community at War -- tSIX. Postbellum Winston and Salem: The Emergence of a Business Class -- tSEVEN. Workers in an Industrial Community -- tEIGHT. The Industrial Community: Drawing the Lines of Class and Race -- tConclusion -- tAPPENDIX A. Rules and Regulations -- tAPPENDIX B. Occupational Classifications for Population Sample from 1850 Census -- tAPPENDIX C. Occupational Classifications for Population Sample from 1880 Census -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1835, Winston and Salem was a well-ordered, bucolic, and attractive North Carolina town. A visitor could walk up Main Street from the village square and get a sense of the quiet Moravian community that had settled here. Yet, over the next half-century, this idyllic village was to experience dramatic changes. The Industrial Revolution calls forth images of great factories, mills, and machinery; yet, the character of the Industrial Revolution went beyond mere changes in modes of production. It meant the radical transformation of economic, social, and political institutions, and the emergence of a new mindset that brought about new ways of thinking and acting. Here is the illuminating story of Winston-Salem, a community of artisans and small farmers united, as members of a religious congregation, by a single vision of life. Transformed in just a few decades from an agricultural region into the home of the smokestacks and office towers of the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company and the Wachovia Bank and Trust Company, the Moravian community at Salem offers an illuminating illustration of the changes that swept Southern society in the nineteenth century and the concomitant development in these communities of a new ethos. Providing a rich wealth of information about the Winston-Salem community specifically, From Congregation Town to Industrial City also significantly broadens our understanding of how wholesale changes in the nineteenth century South redefined the meaning and experience of community. For, by the end of the century, community had gained an entirely new meaning, namely as a forum in which competing individuals pursued private opportunities and interests.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / South (AL, AR, FL, GA, KY, LA, MS, NC, SC, TN, VA, WV).2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814788882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814788882.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPD